title: Whoopi Goldberg and Joy Behar will 'regret' applauding Tucker Carlson's exit
text:
The View hosts Whoopi Goldberg and Joy Behar have been warned by Rubin Report host Dave Rubin they will ‚Äúregret‚Äù their applause after being ‚Äúvery excited‚Äù about Tucker Carlson leaving Fox News.  

‚ÄúI would say congratulations to Whoopi and Joy and the rest of them that you are not going to have to talk about Tucker for a week or two,‚Äù Mr Rubin told Sky News host Paul Murray. 

‚ÄúBut trust me, on the other side, you are going to regret that applause.

‚ÄúTucker is going to come back bigger and stronger than ever ‚Äì he is going to be massive.‚Äù

title: Far-right host Tucker Carlson leaves Fox News in surprise announcement
text:
On Monday, Fox News unexpectedly announced that Tucker Carlson, the network's most popular and controversial presenter, had departed from the channel. 
Subscribe to Guardian News on YouTube ‚ñ∫ http://bit.ly/guardianwiressub

The network released a statement indicating that it had mutually agreed with Carlson to part ways. The statement read: 'Fox News Media and Tucker Carlson have agreed to part ways ... We thank him for his service to the network as a host and prior to that as a contributor.' 
 
Carlson courted controversy throughout his career relying on provocative and inaccurate reporting to boost his ratings. The Los Angeles Times reported his departure was linked to a lawsuit filed by Dominion Voting Systems, which sued the network for defamation after Carlson falsely claimed that the company rigged the 2020 election in favor of Joe Biden.

title: Is A Tucker Carlson And Don Lemon Show In The Works?
text:
Fox News' Tucker Carlson and CNN's Don Lemon are rumored to be texting with each other after their firings from their respective networks, according to Vanity Fair's Brian Stelter. Dr. Rashad Richey and Rickey Smiley discuss on Indisputable. Tell us what you think in the comments below. 

Read more here: https://www.motherjones.com/politics/...

"Could a blossoming kinship, forged in the fire of unceremonious dismissals on the same day, be developing between Tucker Carlson and Don Lemon? 

Maybe. That‚Äôs one of the big takeaways from Brian Stelter, who reports for Vanity Fair that the two men, in addition to retaining the same entertainment lawyer, have reportedly exchanged several texts in the last few days. The content of those messages isn‚Äôt yet known, but I have a feeling they hit the same notes as the statements the two men put out since getting canned: stunned, chaotic, and fuming."

title: WATCH: Tucker Carlson's Mike Tyson Interview Goes Completely Off The Rails
text:
Tucker Carlson interviewed boxing legend Mike Tyson and things got really weird. Jayar Jackson and Adrienne Lawrence break it down on The Watchlist. Watch LIVE on weekdays at noon ET. http://youtube.com/watchlisttyt/live

Read more HERE: https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/arti...

"Conservative political pundit and Fox Host Tucker Carlson didn't want to cramp Mike Tyson's style and offered the boxing legend his home to smoke weed before appearing on his show on Wednesday. 

Though Carlson made it clear that it wasn't 'his thing,' a source told Page Six he had no issue with Tyson getting high before appearing on his Fox Nation streaming show Tucker Carlson Today.

Carlson extended the generous offer, particularly since Tyson admitted he would not be able to get through his show without his daily dose of marijuana.

Tyson gladly accepted, and according to some sources, smoked a 'truckload' worth of weed.  

The undisputed world heavyweight boxer owns a cannabis farm in California and said on his podcast that he and co-host Eben Britton smoke about $40,000 of weed a month, The New York Post reported.  

'Tucker told him that it's not his thing personally, but he had no problem with Mike smoking while he was there,' said a source.

Tyson, whose full name is Michael Gerard Tyson, and known as 'Iron Mike' and 'Kid Dynamite,' is considered one of the great heavyweight boxers of all time."

text:

title: Tucker Carlson re-emerges, targets US media and political system
text:
Former Fox News star Tucker Carlson surfaced publicly on Wednesday (April 27) for the first time since abruptly leaving the network this week, releasing a videotaped statement in which he criticized the state of public discourse on U.S. television.

"Both political parties and their donors have reached consensus on what benefits them and they actively collude to shut down any conversation about it," he said in the videotaped statement posted on Twitter that targeted the American media and the U.S. political system.

Carlson did not directly address his sudden departure from Fox, where he hosted the highest-rated cable news program in the key age demographic on the most-watched U.S. cable news network.

His departure from the network came less than a week after parent company Fox Corp settled for $787.5 million in a defamation lawsuit in which Carlson played a starring role.

title: Bill O'Reilly EXPOSES Tucker Carlson | The Kyle Kulinski Show
text:
Support The Show On Patreon!:
https://www.patreon.com/seculartalk

Subscribe to Krystal Kyle & Friends On Substack!:
https://krystalkyleandfriends.substac...

Follow Kyle on Twitter:
http://www.twitter.com/kylekulinski

"The first time I ever really listened to Kyle Kulinski‚Äôs show was in the back of a cab last summer. The driver had his phone hooked up through the stereo and was pumping out an episode through the car speakers ‚Äî loudly, as if looking to convert a captive audience.

‚ÄúDo you like Kyle Kulinski?‚Äù

The driver, Ahmed, was a recent immigrant and apparently a die-hard fan of Secular Talk, the political talk show that Kulinski broadcasts on YouTube. I told him, yes, in fact. I do like Kulinski, had come across his show several years ago, and, all things considered, he seemed pretty good.

‚ÄúHe understands what we‚Äôre up against,‚Äù Ahmed said. ‚ÄúLike Bernie.‚Äù

But I was surprised to hear Kulinski‚Äôs name mentioned in the same breath as Bernie Sanders, particularly with such adoration. Because what I did remember about Kulinski‚Äôs show struck me as mostly capital-P ‚Äúprogressive‚Äù takes on the news ‚Äî the left wing of the Netroots crowd more than the democratic socialism Sanders has popularized.

It‚Äôs an impression that wasn‚Äôt entirely incorrect.

‚ÄúI have no time for philosophical, airy bullshit,‚Äù Kulinski tells me from his home in Westchester, New York. ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt want to hear about Lenin. I don‚Äôt want to hear about Marx. I just want a super plainspoken, straightforward agenda with a straightforward way of selling it.‚Äù

With over 800,000 subscribers and nearly 670 million total views on YouTube, selling a progressive agenda is clearly something Kulinski knows how to do ‚Äî even Democracy Now, the long-standing flagship of progressive media, cannot match his reach on the platform. Chapo Trap House can certainly boast a wildly devoted fan base (and a not insignificant degree of media influence), but their audience is roughly half the size of Kulinski‚Äôs.

While Secular Talk might be more likely to be looped in with the progressive networks around Air America and Pacifica alums like Sam Seder than the more resolutely socialist world, Kulinski‚Äôs fiery rhetoric, razor-sharp class instincts, and knack for withering takedowns sets him apart from his peers. Judging by his rhetoric alone, he‚Äôs closer to a Eugene Debs than a Chris Hayes.

But unlike Hayes, Amy Goodman, or his friend Cenk Uygur of The Young Turks ‚Äî who began airing Secular Talk on his web network seven years ago ‚Äî the thirty-two-year-old Kulinski is virtually invisible in the mainstream media. Despite his enormous fan base, his show has never once been mentioned in the obligatory trend pieces on ‚Äúthe Millennial Left‚Äù pumped out by the prestige media. Nor has Kulinski‚Äôs name ever popped up at all in the New York Times, Vox, the New Yorker, New York Magazine, or the Washington Post, despite his leading role in cofounding Justice Democrats, the organization widely credited with sweeping Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez and the rest of ‚Äúthe Squad‚Äù to power.

Just last week, his Wikipedia page was deleted. The reason? ‚ÄúThere is very simply no [reliable source] coverage of this person,‚Äù according to one moderator. In new media, he‚Äôs king ‚Äî the Sean Hannity of the Berniecrat left. In old media, he‚Äôs nobody.

I suspect there are a few reasons for that. There is nothing ‚Äúcool‚Äù about Kulinski‚Äôs show. (As a friend put it, ‚Äú‚ÄòWelcome to Secular Talk‚Äô sounds like something you‚Äôd hear on Egyptian radio.‚Äù) His no-nonsense social-democratic politics won‚Äôt get him much cred with the Full Communism crowd. He records his show not in Brooklyn or Los Angeles, but in a studio he built himself in his modest Westchester home. His hair is too groomed and his taste in clothes too preppy to qualify as ‚ÄúDirtbag Left.‚Äù Nor has he ever attended an n+1 release party. ‚ÄúNot only have I not attended one,‚Äù he says, ‚ÄúI have no idea what that means.‚Äù

And yet he‚Äôs astonishingly plugged-in for a young man in the suburbs. Wondering how Sanders ended up on the Joe Rogan Experience? Kulinski, a frequent guest on Rogan‚Äôs wildly popular show, introduced them. ‚ÄúYou make the most sense to me,‚Äù Rogan told Kulinski on a recent episode. ‚ÄúYou‚Äôre a normal person.‚Äù

Much like Sanders himself, Kulinski‚Äôs show has a massive audience that just doesn‚Äôt compute with our media‚Äôs understanding of ‚Äúwhat the kids want‚Äù or even ‚Äúwhat the left-wing kids want.‚Äù

It‚Äôs probably for the best ‚Äî the very woke and very WASP-ish decorum haunting much of the media world is nowhere to be found in Secular Talk. ‚ÄúCorporate Democrats over-focus on identity as a trick to divert you from the issues that unite us all ‚Äî class issues,‚Äù he said on a recent episode.

Read More Here!:
https://jacobinmag.com/2020/03/kyle-k...

title: Tucker Carlson breaks silence after leaving Fox News | New York Post
text:
Former Fox News host Tucker Carlson on Wednesday night made his first remarks since leaving the network and criticized ‚Äúpeople in charge‚Äù of Washington, DC.

In a video posted to Twitter, Carlson ‚Äî who parted ways with Fox News on Monday ‚Äî accused political leaders on both sides of the aisle of silencing voices and shutting down media outlets that uncover corruption or reveal truths.

‚ÄúYou notice when you take a little time off how unbelievably stupid most of the debates you see on television are. They‚Äôre completely irrelevant. They mean nothing. In five years, we won‚Äôt even remember that we have them. Trust me as someone who‚Äôs participated,‚Äù Carlson said.

‚ÄúYet at the same time ‚Äî and this is the amazing thing ‚Äî the undeniably big topics, the ones that will define our future, get virtually no discussion at all: war, civil liberties, emerging science, demographic change, corporate power, natural resources. What was the last time you heard a legitimate debate about any of those issues?"

title: Tucker Carlson breaks silence on Fox firing, targets US media and political system
text:
Former Fox News host Tucker Carlson made his first on-camera appearance Wednesday since his abrupt firing from the network this week, releasing a taped statement in which he criticized the state of political discourse on U.S. television.

In it, he says there has not been a "legitimate debate" about issues including war, civil liberties, natural resources or emerging science for a "long time."

"Both political parties and their donors have reached consensus on what benefits them and they actively collude to shut down any conversation about it," he said.

Carlson, however, did not address his departure from Fox, which came less than a week after parent company Fox Corp settled a $787.5 million defamation lawsuit by Dominion.

title: BREAKING: Tucker Carlson FIRED From Fox News
text:
Support The Show On Patreon!:
https://www.patreon.com/seculartalk

Subscribe to Krystal Kyle & Friends On Substack!:
https://krystalkyleandfriends.substac...

Follow Kyle on Twitter:
http://www.twitter.com/kylekulinski

"The first time I ever really listened to Kyle Kulinski‚Äôs show was in the back of a cab last summer. The driver had his phone hooked up through the stereo and was pumping out an episode through the car speakers ‚Äî loudly, as if looking to convert a captive audience.

‚ÄúDo you like Kyle Kulinski?‚Äù

The driver, Ahmed, was a recent immigrant and apparently a die-hard fan of Secular Talk, the political talk show that Kulinski broadcasts on YouTube. I told him, yes, in fact. I do like Kulinski, had come across his show several years ago, and, all things considered, he seemed pretty good.

‚ÄúHe understands what we‚Äôre up against,‚Äù Ahmed said. ‚ÄúLike Bernie.‚Äù

But I was surprised to hear Kulinski‚Äôs name mentioned in the same breath as Bernie Sanders, particularly with such adoration. Because what I did remember about Kulinski‚Äôs show struck me as mostly capital-P ‚Äúprogressive‚Äù takes on the news ‚Äî the left wing of the Netroots crowd more than the democratic socialism Sanders has popularized.

It‚Äôs an impression that wasn‚Äôt entirely incorrect.

‚ÄúI have no time for philosophical, airy bullshit,‚Äù Kulinski tells me from his home in Westchester, New York. ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt want to hear about Lenin. I don‚Äôt want to hear about Marx. I just want a super plainspoken, straightforward agenda with a straightforward way of selling it.‚Äù

With over 800,000 subscribers and nearly 670 million total views on YouTube, selling a progressive agenda is clearly something Kulinski knows how to do ‚Äî even Democracy Now, the long-standing flagship of progressive media, cannot match his reach on the platform. Chapo Trap House can certainly boast a wildly devoted fan base (and a not insignificant degree of media influence), but their audience is roughly half the size of Kulinski‚Äôs.

While Secular Talk might be more likely to be looped in with the progressive networks around Air America and Pacifica alums like Sam Seder than the more resolutely socialist world, Kulinski‚Äôs fiery rhetoric, razor-sharp class instincts, and knack for withering takedowns sets him apart from his peers. Judging by his rhetoric alone, he‚Äôs closer to a Eugene Debs than a Chris Hayes.

But unlike Hayes, Amy Goodman, or his friend Cenk Uygur of The Young Turks ‚Äî who began airing Secular Talk on his web network seven years ago ‚Äî the thirty-two-year-old Kulinski is virtually invisible in the mainstream media. Despite his enormous fan base, his show has never once been mentioned in the obligatory trend pieces on ‚Äúthe Millennial Left‚Äù pumped out by the prestige media. Nor has Kulinski‚Äôs name ever popped up at all in the New York Times, Vox, the New Yorker, New York Magazine, or the Washington Post, despite his leading role in cofounding Justice Democrats, the organization widely credited with sweeping Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez and the rest of ‚Äúthe Squad‚Äù to power.

Just last week, his Wikipedia page was deleted. The reason? ‚ÄúThere is very simply no [reliable source] coverage of this person,‚Äù according to one moderator. In new media, he‚Äôs king ‚Äî the Sean Hannity of the Berniecrat left. In old media, he‚Äôs nobody.

I suspect there are a few reasons for that. There is nothing ‚Äúcool‚Äù about Kulinski‚Äôs show. (As a friend put it, ‚Äú‚ÄòWelcome to Secular Talk‚Äô sounds like something you‚Äôd hear on Egyptian radio.‚Äù) His no-nonsense social-democratic politics won‚Äôt get him much cred with the Full Communism crowd. He records his show not in Brooklyn or Los Angeles, but in a studio he built himself in his modest Westchester home. His hair is too groomed and his taste in clothes too preppy to qualify as ‚ÄúDirtbag Left.‚Äù Nor has he ever attended an n+1 release party. ‚ÄúNot only have I not attended one,‚Äù he says, ‚ÄúI have no idea what that means.‚Äù

And yet he‚Äôs astonishingly plugged-in for a young man in the suburbs. Wondering how Sanders ended up on the Joe Rogan Experience? Kulinski, a frequent guest on Rogan‚Äôs wildly popular show, introduced them. ‚ÄúYou make the most sense to me,‚Äù Rogan told Kulinski on a recent episode. ‚ÄúYou‚Äôre a normal person.‚Äù

Much like Sanders himself, Kulinski‚Äôs show has a massive audience that just doesn‚Äôt compute with our media‚Äôs understanding of ‚Äúwhat the kids want‚Äù or even ‚Äúwhat the left-wing kids want.‚Äù

It‚Äôs probably for the best ‚Äî the very woke and very WASP-ish decorum haunting much of the media world is nowhere to be found in Secular Talk. ‚ÄúCorporate Democrats over-focus on identity as a trick to divert you from the issues that unite us all ‚Äî class issues,‚Äù he said on a recent episode.

Read More Here!:
https://jacobinmag.com/2020/03/kyle-k...

title: Tucker Carlson‚Äôs ‚Äòstunning, bewildering‚Äô exit from Fox News explained
text:
The US media was ‚Äústunned and bewildered‚Äù following the departure of Tucker Carlson from Fox News, Sky News Australia host Andrew Bolt says.
 
‚ÄúNo one could figure out exactly why Tucker had been sacked or even if he had been sacked, and by whom,‚Äù Mr Bolt said.

‚ÄúTucker was actually sacked ‚Ä¶ by Lachlan Murdoch, the day-to-day boss of News Corp.

‚ÄúAnd the scoop is that he was sacked essentially for thinking that he was bigger than Fox News.‚Äù

title: Tucker Carlson leaves Fox News - BBC News
text:
One of the highest rated US TV hosts, Tucker Carlson, is leaving Fox News, the US media giant has announced.

In a statement, Fox said that the network and Mr Carlson have agreed to "part ways".

His last TV programme was Friday 21 April, the statement added. His primetime slot will now be hosted by a series of interim hosts until a permanent replacement is found.

The brief, two paragraph statement gave no reason for the decision.

The announcement comes just days after Fox News settled a defamation lawsuit from the voting machine company Dominion over its coverage of the 2020 presidential election.

title: What Tucker Carlson's departure could mean for the future of Fox and the GOP
text:
Fox News abruptly announced Monday that its top-rated primetime host Tucker Carlson is leaving the network. The move comes less than a week after Fox agreed to pay $787.5 million to settle a legal battle with Dominion Voting Systems over accusations that its hosts, including Carlson, aired false claims about the 2020 presidential election. title: Why Did Fox Fire Tucker Carlson? Far-Right Host Helped Fox Mainstream Hate, Conspiracies to Millions
text:
In a surprise announcement, Fox News said Monday it was cutting ties with its top-rated host Tucker Carlson, effective immediately. Although a precise reason wasn't given, the move came just days after the cable network settled a $787.5 million defamation suit brought by Dominion Voting Systems over lies propagated by the cable network about the 2020 presidential election. Since taking over the primetime slot in 2016, Carlson has also spread far-right talking points about immigrants, Black people and the LGBTQ community. For more, we speak with Madeline Peltz of Media Matters for America, where she has helped to expose Carlson's extremism. "It creates a major vacuum in the right-wing media ecosystem," Peltz says of Carlson's departure.

title: Newsmax Is Begging Tucker Carlson To Come Save Their Network
text:
According to a report by TMZ, conservative media outlet Newsmax is begging Tucker Carlson to come and save their network. And they aren't just offering him his own show - the report says that they are willing to basically give Carlson complete control of the network. This is further proof that the network has absolutely no standards at all, and they will sacrifice credibility for ratings any day of the week. Farron Cousins explains what's happening. 

Link - https://www.thedailybeast.com/newsmax...

Don't forget to like, comment, and share! And subscribe to stay connected!

Connect with Farron on Twitter: https://twitter.com/farronbalanced

*This transcript was auto-generated. Please excuse any typos.

According to a new report from TMZ out late last week, newsmax, the Conservative outlet that was recently pulled, then re-added to the dying Direct TV lineup, is begging Tucker Carlson to please come and save our network. Now, they're not using the phrase Save Our Network because Newsmax refuses to believe that they're in any kind of trouble. But TMZ says they are begging Tucker Carlson to come and join them, and not just as a host. Of course, he would get his own show, but TMZ is reporting that Newsmax is offer also offering him complete control of the network's programming. Now, if that doesn't scream, save us from ourselves, then I don't know what does. And of course, it's not unlike Newsmax to take Fox's Castaways and put them on the air. They did it with Eric Bowling, who was unceremoniously, of course, removed from Fox News many years ago, and he landed a nice little gig at Newsmax because that's just where all the Fox News rejects go. 

But Newsmax may wanna think twice about offering Tucker Carlson the world to come and save their network. Because it was also reported on Friday that the higher ups at Fox News who have seen these disgusting text messages that were redacted, that eventually both led to his firing and the settlement with Dominion because they were so bad. Fox didn't want them to get out to the public. Newsmax doesn't care. But reports on Friday said that the higher ups at Fox News believed that these text messages from Tucker Carlson were so bad, so disgusting that the network would not have been able to recover from it. Like not just that, oh no, these text messages will make us lose this lawsuit or maybe lose a different lawsuit. They thought that what Tucker Carlson said that, as I said, we don't know what it is yet, but what he said was so bad, Fox News would've been destroyed. 

Newsmax has seen those same reports. Maybe they choose not to believe them, but they know that they're out there. They know that the text messages were bad enough for the network to be like, we're gonna get rid of our highest rated, the highest rated host in all of cable news. We're gonna can him because of what he said. And Newsmax is out there. Say like, we'll take him. We'll give you complete control of our network. You disgusting, horrid human being, whatever it takes to get a couple more dollars in our pockets, right? Newsmax, do you really, this is a rhetorical question that we already know the answer to, but do you really have such low standards, both morally, ethically, 

Business wise, that you're willing to take on such a liability that even Fox News was like, dude, this is too much for us. Are you willing to sync that loan news Max? Yes, of course you are because you want the ratings, right? You want that sweet, sweet money ignoring, of course, the fact that 26 major advertisers had already pulled all their ads from Tucker Carlson's program. Typically, the ads run during Tucker Carlson's show were either for MyPillow, even though the guy claims he hates Fox, he's still advertising there. Or they were promos for other Fox News shows. Yes, they were paying Tucker a pretty penny because they were hoping that the audience would either tune in early so they could get a couple ads in there or stay after so they could get some ads in there. But the major advertisers weren't running stuff on Tucker's show, so he basically became more of an expense than a profit generating machine. But Newsmax, if you want to take that hit, if you wanna show the entire country that you have absolutely no scruples whatsoever, that you will literally do anything for ratings and or a dollar, then by all means, continue pursuing Tucker Carlson.

title: Tucker Carlson Posts WEAK Response To Getting Fired By Fox News
channelName: The Majority Report w/ Sam Seder
text:
Tucker Carlson, the former host of Fox News's "Tucker Carlson Tonight," has posted a cryptic social media message in response to his firing from the network.

In the message, Carlson speaks broadly about the lack of debate on television and the state of the news media. He does not directly address his firing, but he does say that he is "grateful for the opportunity" he had at Fox News.

Carlson's firing comes after the network settled a $787.5 million defamation lawsuit with Dominion Voting Systems. The lawsuit alleged that Carlson and Fox News had defamed Dominion by spreading false claims about the company's role in the 2020 election.

Fox kept their controversial cash cow around until they got into a bit of trouble of their own. They were sued by Dominion Voting Systems for defamation. The network‚Äôs programs alleged that the company‚Äôs technology was used to rig the 2020 election in favor of Joe Biden. Tucker Carlson Tonight was one of them. The case was settled out of court to the tune of $787.5 million. It wasn‚Äôt as much as Dominion wanted, but it sent a message and kept Fox‚Äôs secrets safe. The network fired Tucker soon after news of the settlement became public. It was sudden, shocking his colleagues and even President Trump himself.

The reason for his departure isn‚Äôt clear. It could have been his role in the defamation lawsuit, his other suit from Abby Grosberg, his controversial comments about upper management, or a combination of all of the above. Fans will miss Tucker‚Äôs nightly broadcasts, but losing him isn‚Äôt the worst part. The real damage, as he insinuated early, is the loss of trust. Americans are more convinced than ever that they can‚Äôt trust their news media to tell them the truth.

text:
"Briahna Joy Gray and Robby Soave react to Robert F. Kennedy Jr's interview with Tucker Carlson. #rfk #2024 #biden Disclaimer: According to the CDC, all COVID-19 vaccines currently available in the United States are effective at preventing COVID-19. Getting sick with COVID-19 can offer some protection from future illness, sometimes called ‚Äúnatural immunity,‚Äù but the level of protection people get from having COVID-19 may vary depending on how mild or severe their illness was, the time since their infection, and their age.

Getting a COVID-19 vaccination is also a safer way to build protection than getting sick with COVID-19. COVID-19 vaccination helps protect you by creating an antibody response without you having to experience sickness. Getting vaccinated yourself may also protect people around you, particularly people at increased risk for severe illness from COVID-19. Getting sick with COVID-19 can cause severe illness or death, and we can‚Äôt reliably predict who will have mild or severe illness. If you get sick, you can spread COVID-19 to others. You can also continue to have long-term health issues after COVID-19 infection.

While COVID-19 vaccines are effective, studies have shown some declines in vaccine effectiveness against infections over time, especially when the Delta variant was circulating widely.

The mRNA vaccines do not contain any live virus. Instead, they work by teaching our cells to make a harmless piece of a ‚Äúspike protein,‚Äù which is found on the surface of the virus that causes COVID-19. After making the protein piece, cells display it on their surface. Our immune system then recognizes that it does not belong there and responds to get rid of it. When an immune response begins, antibodies are produced, creating the same response that happens in a natural infection.

In contrast to mRNA vaccines, many other vaccines use a piece of, or weakened version of, the germ that the vaccine protects against. This is how the measles and flu vaccines work. When a weakened or small part of the virus is introduced to your body, you make antibodies to help protect against future infection.

Everyone ages 18 and older should get a booster shot either 6 months after their initial Pfizer or Moderna series, or 2 months after their initial Johnson & Johnson‚Äôs Janssen vaccine. People ages 16‚Äì17 may get a booster dose of Pfizer at least 6 months after their initial series of vaccines.

The CDC says A person is fully vaccinated two weeks after receiving all recommended doses in the primary series of their COVID-19 vaccination. A person is up to date with their COVID-19 vaccination if they have received all recommended doses in the primary series and one booster when eligible.

Getting a second booster is not necessary to be considered up to date at this time. A study by The Cleveland Clinic found that both previous infection and vaccination provide substantial protection against COVID-19. Vaccination of previously infected individuals does not provide additional protection against COVID-19 for several months, but after that provides significant protection at least against symptomatic COVID-19."

title: Tucker Carlson sent a racist text to a producer: 'It's not how white men fight'
text:
CNN ‚Äî In a newly revealed text message, ousted Fox News host Tucker Carlson made a racist comment and said he found himself briefly rooting for a mob of Trump supporters to kill a person.
"A couple of weeks ago, I was watching video of people fighting on the street in Washington," Carlson texted a producer. "A group of Trump guys surrounded an Antifa kid and started pounding the living s**t out of him. It was three against one, at least. Jumping a guy like that is dishonorable obviously. It's not how white men fight. Yet suddenly I found myself rooting for the mob against the man, hoping they'd hit him harder, kill him. I really wanted them to hurt the kid. I could taste it." The text was one of a trove of messages from Carlson and other Fox News hosts uncovered in a defamation lawsuit filed by Dominion Voting Systems against the network for airing false allegations that the company's machines were used to steal the 2020 election from former President Donald Trump.

The sides settled just as the trial was getting underway, with Fox agreeing to pay Dominion nearly $800 million.

While some of Carlson's texts have been publicly released, the one quoted by the Times remains redacted by the court, as do numerous other exhibits. Media organizations, including The Associated Press, continue to try to lift the redactions.

The Times reports that Carlson sent the text to a producer hours after Trump supporters attacked the U.S. Capitol on Jan. 6, 2021. He describes a video he had seen a couple of weeks earlier of Trump supporters beating someone he described as ‚Äúan Antifa kid.‚Äù

Carlson wrote about his conflicting emotions in watching the fight, which he described as ‚Äúthree against one, at least.‚Äù

‚ÄúJumping a guy like that is dishonorable obviously,‚Äù he wrote, according to the Times. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs not how white men fight.‚Äù

‚ÄúI should remember that somewhere somebody probably loves this kid, and would be crushed if he was killed,‚Äù Carlson wrote, after admitting part of him was rooting for the attackers. ‚ÄúIf I don‚Äôt care about those things, if I reduce people to their politics, how am I better than he is?‚Äù

Before his ouster last month, Carlson was Fox's top-rated host. He drew controversy for supporting theories such as the idea that immigrants are being admitted to the U.S to ‚Äúreplace‚Äù people born here. Critics have called that white supremacy, an accusation he has denied.

Messages sent Wednesday to Carlson and his attorney seeking comment were not immediately returned.

text:

Suddenly, right as the Dominion Defamation Trial began, decided to work out a settlement with the company. And it all comes down to what Tucker did. According to a massive new report from the New York Times, there were more Tucker Carlson text messages that were a part of the Dominion lawsuit that the public didn't get to see. Now, I don't always like saying I told you so, but that is 100% what I sat right here and told y'all was going to happen. I told y'all that the text messages we had already seen as bad as they were, were just the tip of the iceberg because those were only revealed because Dominion had to reveal them in their court filings to fight back other motions filed by Fox News. And that the real juicy stuff. And honestly, I think I said this like two weeks ago, the real juicy stuff wasn't gonna come out until the trial. 

Turns out I was a hundred percent right, but we, the public weren't the only people who were expecting horrible text messages to come out because apparently in the redacted court filings that the Fox News Board of directors and other executives only received the night before the trial began. They got to see these horrific text messages that unfortunately we still don't know the contents of, but they were from Tucker Carlson. Several of them had him referring to women by the C word. Um, others were, you know, very graphic, very disturbing, very disparaging, you know, possibly a little bit of bigotry tossed in there we're not a hundred percent certain, but the text messages were so bad. The content in them was so obscene according to the people that have seen them, that it would've cost the network bid ti big time. Like they were so afraid of these text messages becoming public, that they paid Dominion voting systems, 787 million, just so the public wouldn't see these text messages. That's how bad they were. 787 million. To not show you what Tucker Carlson was saying in private, that is a hefty price tag. And that, of course, according to this report and according to the analysis, is what not only led to the settlement, but then eventually led to his firing a week later, earlier this week. So how bad are those text messages? We don't know, but apparently bad enough 

To be willing to write a check for 787 million. Now here's the thing. Fox's own lawyers had these text messages, right? They knew about 'em, but they didn't tell their own clients until the night before. Like they're getting ready to go to bed. Like, all right guys, sleep tight. We got a big trial tomorrow. Oh, by the way, have you seen these texts from Tucker Carlson? Woo, boy, they're bad. Well, anyway, goodnight fire those lawyers immediately, like fi, they should have been fired before you fire Tucker Carlson, because that is absolutely horrific. Of course, if you had negotiated a settlement months ago, then the lawyers wouldn't have been able to still keep working on the Dominion case, so they wouldn't have gotten paid. 

So you got screwed at least twice. But those lawyers ought to be fired. I mean, honest to God, these lawyers at this point, I believe, need to be investigated because you withheld evidence from your own client so that you could continue the case so you would continue to get paid.
